## Progress Flag Nails: Beyond the Six-Colour Rainbow

Three coats. That is roughly how long it takes to build the chevron of the <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progress_flag' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>Progress Pride Flag</a> onto a nail  but the meaning behind those extra stripes is worth understanding before you pick up the brush. Created in 2018 by designer Daniel Quasar, the Progress flag added a five-colour chevron to the classic rainbow: black and brown to represent marginalised communities of colour, and light blue, pink, and white from the trans flag. The forward-pointing arrow shape signals progress still in motion. As of 2026, the <a href='https://www.intomore.com/culture/identity/everything-ever-wanted-know-progress-flag/' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>Progress flag meaning</a> has only deepened  this is the flag most commonly flown at institutional and civic celebrations, and the one many community members now consider the default.

On nails, the chevron reads best on longer lengths, but skittle nails using the chevron colours  one nail black, one brown, one light blue, one pink, one white  work on any length and are the most accessible DIY version. See <a href='/blog/pride-flag-nails'>every identity flag in detail</a> for stamp designs and step-by-step breakdowns.

